'''Bubbe meise''' or "bobe maysse" ({{lang-yi|באבע מאיסע}}) is an expression meaning "old wives tale", literally "grandmother's tale", essentially "a fairytale of something impossible". The Yiddish word "bubbe" is close to [[Slavic peoples|Slavic]] "grandmother", such as {{lang-ru|баба}}. 

The roots of this expression lie in [[Medieval]] [[Anglo-Norman]] [[chivalry|chivalric]] adventures [[Romance (genre)|romance]] ''Sir [[Bevis of Hampton]]''. Rewritten in Yiddish for [[Jew]]ish audience in [[1507]]–[[1508]] by [[Elia Levita]], and printed in [[1541]], it came to be known as ''Bove meise'' or ''[[Bovo-Bukh]]'' and for five centuries has been the most popular chivalric romance in the Yiddish language. 

